correct_answer: The system has infinitely many solutions depending on two parameters.
answer2: The system has infinitely many solutions depending on one parameter.

question:
Find the solutions of the following linear system:
$$\begin{cases}
x & + & y & - & 3z & + & 2t & = & 1 \\
2x & - & y & - & z & + & t & = & 0 \\
x & + & y & + & z & - & t & = & -2
\end{cases}$$
correct_answer: The solutions of the system are of the form $\bigg(-\frac{2}{3},\frac{1}{4}t-\frac{7}{12},\frac{3}{4}t-\frac{3}{4},t\bigg)$, for all $t\in\mathbb{R}$.
answer3: The system has $\bigg(-\frac{2}{3},-\frac{7}{12},-\frac{3}{4},0\bigg)$ as unique solution.
answer4: The solution of the system is the vector of coordinates $(2,-1,0,0)$.

question:
Find the solutions $\left(\text{in } \mathbb{C}^2\right)$ of the following linear system:
$$\begin{cases}
(1+i)z& + & (1-i)w & = & i \\
(1-i)z& + & (1+i)w & = & 1-i
\end{cases}$$
correct_answer: The unique solution of the linear system is $\bigg(\frac{3+i}{4},-\frac{1+i}{4}\bigg)$.
answer2: The solutions of the linear system are of the form $\bigg(\frac{1+i}{4},\frac{-1+i}{4}+z\bigg)$, for every $z\in\mathbb{C}$.
answer3: The linear system has no solutions.
answer4: The linear system has the vector $(i,-i)$ has its unique solution.

z'(t)=-x+2y+3z
\end{cases}$

z(t)=C_{1}e^{2t}+2C_{2}e^{3t}\cos t+3C_{3}e^{3t}\sin t,
\end{cases}$
where $C_{1}, C_{2}, C_{3} \in \mathbb{R}$.

$\begin{cases}

\end{cases}$

question:
Letting $j := e^{\frac{2i\pi}{3}}$, find the solutions of the following linear system depending on the values of the parameters $a,b\in\mathbb{C}$:
$$\begin{cases}

 &  & j^{2}y & + & jz & = & b
\end{cases}$$
correct_answer:
The system has no solutions if $a+b\neq 0$. 

If $b=-a$, then for every $a\in\mathbb{C}$ the system has $\left(\frac{a+(1+2j)z}{1+j},\,\frac{a+jz}{1+j},\,z\right)$ as solution for every $z\in\mathbb{C}$.
answer2: The system has no solution for every value of $a$ and $b$.
answer3: The system has $\left(0,0,0\right)$ as its unique solution if $a=b=0$, and for all other values of $a$ and $b$ the system has no solutions.
answer4: For every $a,b\in\mathbb{C}$ the system has $\left(\frac{a+(1+2j)z}{1+j},\,\frac{a+jz}{1+j},\,z\right)$ as solution for every $z\in\mathbb{C}$.

question:

answer2: The system has no solution for every $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$.
answer3:
If $b\neq a+1$, the system has no solutions.

answer4:
If $b=a+1$ the system has no solution. 

Otherwise, for every $a,b \in \mathbb{R}$ the system has a unique solution, which is $\left(\frac{a+b+1}{20},\,\frac{-a-b+2}{3},\,\frac{2a+3b-4}{15}\right)$.

answer2: The system has no solutions for every $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$.

question:
Find the solutions of the following linear system depending on the values of the parameters $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$:

 &  & ay & + & az & = & ab \\

\end{cases}$$

If $a=b=0$, the system has $\left(x,\,y,\,1-x-y\right)$ as solution for every $x,y\in\mathbb{R}$.
If $a=0$ and $b\neq 0$, the system has $\left(x,\,1-x,\,0\right)$ as solution for every $x\in\mathbb{R}$.

The system has no solutions for $a\neq b$. 
If $a=b=0$, the system has $\left(x,\,y,\,1-x-y\right)$ as its solution for every $x,y\in\mathbb{R})$. 
If $a=b\neq 0$, the system has $\left(x,\,1-x,\,0\right)$ as its solution for every $x\in\mathbb{R}$.
answer3: The system has $\left(b-a,\,b^{2}-a,\,\frac{b^{2}-a}{2a^{2}+1}\right)$ as its unique solution for every $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$.
answer4:
If $a=b=0$, the system has $\left(x,\,y,\,1-x-y\right)$ as its solution for every $x,y\in\mathbb{R}^{2}$. 
If $a=0$ and $b\neq 0$, the system has no solutions.
If $a\neq 0$ and $b=0$, the system has $\left(x,\,0,\,x\right)$ as its solution for every $x\in\mathbb{R}$.
If $a,b\neq 0$, the system has $\left(x+a,\,y-\frac{b}{a},\,1-ax-by\right)$ as its solution for every $x,y\in\mathbb{R}$.

question: Differentiate $y=\dfrac{(x+3)^2}{x}$.

Consider the real function $f:\mathbb{R}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}$ defined by $f(x):=2x^{2}-6x+5$. Find all real numbers $a,b,c\in\mathbb{R}$ such that $$f(x)=ax+bx(x-1)+c(x-1)(x-2)$$for every $x\in\mathbb{R}$.

The WorldLight Company produces two light fixtures (products $1$ and $2$) that require both metal frame parts and electrical components. Management wants to determine how many units of each product to produce so as to maximize profit. For each unit of product $1$, $1$ unit of frame parts and $2$ units of electrical components are required. For each unit of product $2$, $3$ units of frame parts and $2$ units of electrical components are required. The company has $200$ units of frame parts and $300$ units of electrical components. 

Each unit of product $1$ gives a profit of $1$, and each unit of product $2$, up to $60$ units, gives a profit of $2$. Any excess over	$60$ units of product $2$ brings no profit, so such excess has been ruled out.
	
In this situation, what are the decision variables to formalize the Linear Programming (LP) model that allows planning the company's activity?
correct_answer: $x_{i}$ the number of units of product $i$ produced ($i=1$, for product $A$ and $i=2$, for product $B$).
answer2: $x$ the number of units of product $1$ and $2$ produced.
answer3: $x_{1}$ is the number of units of product $1$ produced.
answer4: $x_{2}$ is the number of units of product $2$ produced.

question:

a_{4_1} & a_{4_2} & a_{4_3} & a_{4_4} & a_{4_5} & a_{4_6} & \dots \\

question:

question:
Consider the sequence $$0, 1, \frac{1}{2}, \frac{3}{4}, \frac{5}{8}, \frac{11}{16}, \dots$$ in which each term is the average of the previous two terms. 

Find the formula for the general term using a recurrence equation $(a_n)_{n \in\ \mathbb{N}}$. Make sure you state the initial condition. Then give a formula for the general term.
correct_answer:
The recurrence equation is $a_n=\frac{1}{2}\left(a_{n-2}+a_{n-1}\right), \ \forall n \geq 2$.

The initial condition is $a_0=0$.

The closed formula is $a_n=\frac{2}{3}-\frac{2}{3}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^n, \ \forall n \geq 0$.
answer2:
The recurrence equation is $a_n=\frac{1}{2}\left(a_{n-2}+a_{n-1}\right), \ \forall n \geq 3$.

The initial condition is $a_1=0$.

The closed formula is $a_n=\frac{2}{3}-\frac{2}{3}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^n, \ \forall n \geq 1$.
answer3:
The recurrence equation is $a_n=\frac{1}{2}\cdot a_{n-2}+a_{n-1}, \ \forall n \geq 3$.

The initial condition is $a_1=0$.

The closed formula is $a_n=-\frac{2}{3}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^n, \ \forall n \geq 1$.
answer4:
The recurrence equation is $a_n=\frac{1}{2}\left(a_{n-2}+a_{n-1}\right), \ \forall n \geq 2$.

The initial condition is $a_0=0$.

The closed formula is $a_n=-\frac{2}{3}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^n, \ \forall n \geq 0$.

question: Choose the wrong statement.
correct_answer: In a translation, the orientation of the angles is inverted.
answer2: Translation, rotations, reflections and sliding reflections are isometries.

question: If $A = \left\{x : x \in \mathbb{N}, 1 \leq x < 10 \right\},\, B$ is the set of odd numbers smaller than $10$ and $C = \left\{ 2,4,6,8,10 \right\}$ in the universal set $\mathbb{N}$, which of the following statement is true?

Find the domain and the image of the function
$$f(x,y)=\sqrt{9-x^2}-\sqrt{4-y^2}.$$
correct_answer:
The domain is $\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\ -3\leq x\leq 3,\ -2\leq y\leq 2\right\}$ and the image is the interval
$\left[-2,3\right]$.
answer2:
The domain is $\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\ -3< x< 3,\ -2< y< 2\right\}$ and the image is the interval
$\left[0,1\right]$.
answer3:
The domain is $\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\ -3\leq x\leq 3,\ -2\leq y\leq 2\right\}$ and the image is the interval
$\left[0,1\right]$.
answer4:
The domain is $\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\ -3\leq x\leq 3,\ -2\leq y\leq 2\right\}$ and the image is the interval
$\left[0,+\infty\right)$.

question:
A preserved fruit company owns two factories ($j$). The fruit can be provided by three producers ($j$) under the following conditions: producer A sells 200 tonne at 10 u.m. per tonne, producer B sells 300 tonne at 9 u.m. per tonne and Producer C sells 400 tonne at 8 u.m. per tonne.

The transportation costs (u.m./tonne) between each factory and producer are the following:
	\[
\begin{array}{l|cc|}
 & \text{Factory 1} & \text{Factory 2} \\

The capacities of the factories as well as the cost of labor are the following:
	\[

Find the domain and the image of the function
$$f(x,y,z)=\displaystyle{-\frac{z^2}{\sqrt{x^2-y^2}}}.$$
correct_answer:
The domain is the set of all points $(x,y,z)$ with $|y|<|x|$ and the image is the interval
$\left(-\infty,0\right]$.
answer2:
The domain is the set of all points $(x,y,z)$ with $|y|\leq |x|$ and the image is the interval
$\left(-\infty,0\right]$.
answer3:
The domain is the set of all points $(x,y,z)$ with $y<x$ and the image is the interval
$\left(-\infty,0\right)$.
answer4:
The domain is the set of all points $(x,y,z)$ with $y<x$ and the image is the 
$\mathbb{R}$.

question:
A distribution company owns two warehouses (i) in the south of the country (W1 and W2). From these points, the company needs to supply its customers (j) in four cities, C1, C2, C3  and C4 (one customer per city). The transport cost for each tonne of material is 100 u.m./km. The following table shows the distances to be traveled between the two warehouses and the various cities (in km):

	\[
\begin{array}{l|cccc|}
& C_1 & C_2 & C_3  &  C_4\\
\hline
W_1 & 100 & 85 & 270  & 500 \\
W_2 & -  & 185 & 185 & 150\\
\hline
\end{array}
\]	

The requirements of customers C1, C2, C3 and C4 are respectively 200, 250, 400 and 150 tonnes. The inventory in both warehouses W1 and W2 is 200 and 500 tonnes, respectively. The company has established agreements with the various customers, setting the following prices to charge (u.m./ton):

	\[
\begin{array}{l|cccc|}
& C_1 & C_2 & C_3  &  C_4\\
\hline
W_1 & 10500  & 9250 & 27570  & 50870\\
W_2 & - & 19150 & 18600 & 15220\\
\hline
\end{array}
\]	

Determine the optimal solution, formulating a transport problem.
For any set $A$, what is $A \cup \emptyset$ ?

$$f(x,y)=\left\{\begin{array}{cl}

\displaystyle\frac{1}{6},& (x,y)=(0,0).
\end{array}\right.$$
correct_answer:
The domenin is $D=\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\  x^2+ y^2\leq 9\right\}$, the image is $\left[\displaystyle\frac{1}{6},\displaystyle\frac{1}{3}\right]$
and $f$ is continuous on $D$.
answer2:
The domenin is $D=\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\  x^2+ y^2\leq 9\right\}$, the image is $\left[0,3\right]$
and $f$ is continuous on $D$.
answer3:
The domenin is $D=\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\  x^2+ y^2\leq 9\right\}$, the image is $\left[0,3\right]$
and $f$ is continuous on $D\setminus\{(0,0)\}$.
answer4:
The domenin is $D=\left\{(x,y)\in \mathbb{R}^2\mid\  x^2+ y^2\leq 9\right\}$, the image is $\left[\displaystyle\frac{1}{6},\displaystyle\frac{1}{3}\right]$
and $f$ is continuous on $D\setminus\{(0,0)\}$.

question:
A company has three production centres: C1, C2 and C3. These centres supply four major markets: Porto (MP), Coimbra (MC), Lisboa (ML) and Faro (MF). The transport costs per unit, between each centre and each market are indicated in the following table (u.m.):
\[
\begin{array}{l|cccc|}
& \text{MP} & \text{MC} & \text{ML}  & \text{MF}\\
\hline
C_1 & 5 & 8 & 10  & 12\\
C_2 & 10  & 4 & 9  & 10\\
C_3 & 7  & 8 & 10 & 6\\
\hline 
\end{array}
\]
The monthly production capacities of each centre are: 1500, 1500 and 1000 (for $C_1$, $C_2$ and $C_3$, respectively). The sale price of each product varies with the market where it is sold, being 100, 90, 110 and 950 u.m. respectively for the markets MP, MC, ML and MF. The requirements of these markets are respectively 1200, 600, 2000 and 500 units. The production costs may be considered constant for the three centres. Determine the optimal monthly distribution plan.

Find $\ell_1=\lim\limits_{x\to 0}(\lim\limits_{y\to 0}f(x,y)),$ $\ \ell_2=\lim\limits_{y\to 0}(\lim\limits_{x\to 0}f(x,y)),$ and
$\ell=\lim\limits_{(x,y)\to (0,0)}f(x,y),$ where
$$f(x,y)=\displaystyle x^2\sin^2\displaystyle\frac{1}{y^2}+\displaystyle y^2\cos^2\displaystyle\frac{1}{x^2}.$$

The differentiable function $f:\{\,(x,y,z)\in \mathbb{R}^{3};x>0,\,z\neq 0\}\rightarrow \mathbb{R},\, f(x,y,z)=\dfrac{xy}{z}\cdot\ln x+x\cdot\varphi \left (\dfrac{y}{x},\dfrac{z}{x}\right),$ where $\varphi:\mathbb{R}\rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ is a $\mathcal{C}^{1}-$class function, satisfies the equation:
correct_answer: $x\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x}+y\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y}+z\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial z}=f+\dfrac{xy}{z};$
answer2: $x\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x}+y\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y}+z\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial z}=f;$
answer3: $\dfrac{1}{x}\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\dfrac{1}{y}\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\dfrac{1}{z}\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial z}=\dfrac{f}{x^{2}}+\dfrac{xy}{z};$
answer4: $\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x}+\dfrac{y}{x}\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y}+\dfrac{z}{x}\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial z}=f+\dfrac{y}{z}.$

question:

Allocate each person to each vacancy in order to maximize the sum of the classifications of the three people.

	\[

& A & B & C  \\

W_2 & 8  & 10 & 10 \\
W_3 & 10  &  12  & 8\\
W_4 & 8 &  15 & 10 \\
\hline  
\end{array}
\]		
Workers 1 and 2 want a monthly salary of 160 and 130 u.m. respectively; the workers 3 and 4 want 110 u.m. each one. Find the partial derivatives $\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}, \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}, \frac{\partial f}{\partial z}$ of the function
$f:\{\,(x,y,z)\in \mathbb{R}^{3};\,y\neq z\}\rightarrow \mathbb{R},\, f(x,y,z)=x^{3}y^{2}z+\sin (xy)-\frac{x}{y-z}.$
correct_answer:
$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=3x^{2}y^{2}z+y\cos (xy)-\frac{1}{y-z},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=2x^{3}yz+x\cos (xy)+\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}=x^{3}y^{2}-\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}}$
answer2:
$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=3x^{2}y^{2}z-y\cos (xy)-\frac{1}{y-z},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=2x^{3}yz+x\cos (xy)-\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}=x^{3}y^{2}-\frac{1}{(y-z)^{2}}$
answer3:
$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=3x^{2}y^{2}z+y\cos (xy)-\frac{1}{y-z},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=2x^{3}yz+x\cos (xy)-\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}=x^{3}y^{2}+\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}}$
answer4:
$\frac{\partial f}{\partial x}=3x^{2}y^{2}z+y\cos (xy)-\frac{1}{y-z},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial y}=2x^{3}yz+x\cos (xy)+\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}},$

$\frac{\partial f}{\partial z}=x^{3}y^{2}+\sin (xy)-\frac{x}{(y-z)^{2}}$
